<br>
What do you suppose would be the best pusher plate design for an orion? How would you solve the problems of:<br>
<br>
1) Erosion or How to build a plate than can withstand 2000 .2kt pulses. <br>
<br>
2) Resonance or How to control or eliminate plate resonance that could damage the structure or crew.<br>
<br>
3) Initial shock absorbtion and plate return compliance.<br>
<br>
We have all studied the various orion schemes and these appear to be problems that were not completely solved. <br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tim1965>Tim1965</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 276<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/25/03 12:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=337.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: open question: &quot;pusher plate design&quot;</span><hr size=1> To get all the research on these things you should go to barns and noble book sellers, and arrange to purchase a Project Orion report, or a book about the orion project. There is good book out about this now called project Orion written by the son of freemon dyson whose father worked on the  origonal orion project.<br>
