 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dustyslaunchpad>Dustys Launchpad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 173<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/25/03 3:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=337.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: open question: &quot;pusher plate design&quot;</span><hr size=1> A couple of thoughts, in no particular order. <br>
<br>
1) Modern ceramics have properties that 1950’s engineers could only dream about.<br>
<br>
2) If the pusher plate was magnetised with superconducting coils, could this absorb the impulse of the plasma with reduced (or even zero) actual physical contact (it would probably generate fairly impressive EMP though!!<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :evil --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/devil.gif ALT=":evil"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> )<br>
<br>
3) Whilst it would certainly cause problems in other areas, would a higher pulse rate reduce at least some of the pusher plate design difficulties?  Most Orion designs seem to go for a pulse rate of about 1/second. This means a large pusher plate mass (around 25%) relative to the rest of the ship and consequently massive shocks and springs. Daedulus had a pulse rate of 250/second and basically didn’t have a pusher plate, as such, at all.<br>
<br>
I can’t see fission PU’s firing at anything like that rate but on a large Orion (40,000 ton plus) 10/second might be possible if a reliable ejector mech was possible. (I think this would allow a pusher plate mass of 2.5% ship mass, still massive but possibly easier to handle.)<br>
<br>
4) I am assuming launch capable Orion’s here. Orion’s built in orbit have a much less demanding operational envelope. You could do small NPU’s once every 10 seconds or more and have a longer boost phase. This would allow one to have heavy “return” damping (IYSWIM) in order to reduce stress and vibration. <br>
<br>
5) Pulse unit design would have a significant effect on the engineering of the pusher plate. EG there is a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>huge</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> difference between the effects of, say, being hit by a 1Kg brick travelling at 10M/s once per second and being on the receiving end of a jet of water flowing at 1Kg/s travelling at 10 M/s. the bricks would kill you fairly quickly whereas you would probably hardly notice the water! Yet the impulse in both cases is the same. Designing the pulse units to produce more of a squirt and less of a bang would reduce the peak stresses on the spacecraft<br>
<br>
I dare say i will think of a few more points later<br>
<br>
