<br>
2. I would start limiting the impulse acting on the crew (this requires some careful calculation of the total ship mass w.r.t. force per pulse, and affects the total required plate surface as well). As far as structure safety is concerned, collimation of detonation point with the plate axis is a must, and proper margins on plate thickness have to be adopted to cope with undue displacement of detonation point. Resonance can be avoided by placing damping elements within the crew-hosting structure (structural simulation helps determining where to place such elements). <br>
<br>
3. Massive damping systems coupling plate to crew-hosting structure seem to be the only viable solution. The impulse response of the damping systems must be shaped so to produce the desired output impulse-to-crew profile.<br>
<br>
I would solve first problem 1, then problem 3 and finally problem 2. Note that the solutions to these problems have to be looped together.<br>
<br>
The first step is to write down the list of design model parameters (what you can change within some lower and upper bound) and design model variables (what you can control only by changing parameters).<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=flytothestars>FlyToTheStars</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/14/03 9:31 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=337.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Pusher Plate Design (2)</span><hr size=1> For Damping System design, you must consider the desired Impulse to Crew Hosting Structure vs. Time (ITCHS Time Profile) as a parameter. I would use a two-stage design.<br>
<br>
The first stage of the Damping System must transform the Pulse Impulse Time profile (PI Time Profile) into the desired ITCHS Time Profile. To this end, consider the differences in frequency spectra of ITCHS Time Profile and PI Time Profile. Frequencies that are in both spectra have to be equalized (change their amplitude  to match ITCHS spectrum), frequencies that are in the PI spectrum only have to be filtered out (see below).<br>
<br>
Given the ITCHS Time Profile, you have to consider its frequency spectrum, and see what frequency carries the highest energy to CHS. Knowing it, you design the second stage of the Damping System to filter out that frequency, using a properly designed mechanical phase shifter for that frequency. You can repeat the procedure until all dangerous frequencies are filtered out, by cascading filtering elements, highest energy filtering elements first.<br>
<br>
Both stages have an identical design, they only work on different frequency sets and energy levels.<br>
