<br>
This info raise a doubt in my mind.<br>
<br>
A non-spherical plasma blob would produce a non-symmetric emission of motion quantity. Thus, the device devoted to the production of the plasma jet would be accelerated in the opposite direction while it is shaping the plasma blob.<br>
<br>
It seems to me that any non-spherical plasma blob would be &quot;stretched&quot; along the plasma jet propagation axis, due to the relative motion of the PU and of the Orion vehicle. Thus, the first part of the plasma jet would have a relative speed (w.r.t. the Orion vehicle) higher than the last part. This would lead to a non-symmetrical pressure wave shape (something like a saw-tooth).<br>
<br>
This effect would reduce the overall efficiency of the PU. The more you focuse the plasma blob, the higher the slope of both edges of the pressure wave.<br>
<br>
There must be an optimal trade-off involving PU total mass, PU propellant mass, plasma jet shape/focusing factor and PU propellant speed. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=flytothestars>FlyToTheStars</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/30/03 4:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=337.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   PU units</span><hr size=1> Agreed :-)...<br>
